04090nam a22005055i 9780773564428DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19941994xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735644287 a10.1515/97807735644282doi  a(DE-B1597)658022  a(OCoLC)1394872392  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aE359.85 ǂb S49 1994eb 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a971.03/41 aSheppard, George, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPlunder, Profit, and Paroles :bA Social History of the War of 1812 in Upper Canada /cGeorge Sheppard. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1994] 4c©1994  a1 online resource (344 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables, Maps, and Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t"A Motley Population": Prewar Upper Canada -- t"Cool Calculators": Brock's Militia -- t"A Parcel of Quakers?" Militia Service, 1813—15 -- t"A Grand Attack on the Onions": Provisions and Plundering -- t"Enemies at Home": Treacherous Thieves -- t"Success to Commerce": Costs and Claims -- t"The Most Puzzling Question": War Losses Politics -- t"A Greater Degree of Patriotism": Developing Nationalism -- tColonial Accounts -- tGourlay's Township Meetings -- tA Note on Methods and Sources -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSheppard demonstrates that the colony was a fragmented and pluralistic community before the war and remained so after it. Upper Canadians were divided by racial, religious, linguistic, and class differences and the majority of settlers had no strong ties to either the United States or Britain, with most men avoiding military service during the war. Reviewing the claims submitted for damages attributed to the fighting, he argues that British forces as well as enemy troops were responsible for widespread destruction of private property and concludes that this explains why there was little increase in anti-American feeling after the war. Much of the wartime damage occurred in areas west of York (now Toronto). This was the cause of grievances harboured by settlers in the western part of Upper Canada against their eastern counterparts long after the war had ended. As well, some Upper Canadians profited from wartime activities while others suffered greatly. Only later, in the 1840s when these issues had faded from memory, did Canadians begin to create a favourable version of wartime events. Using garrison records, muster rolls, diaries, newspapers, and damage claims registered after the war, the author delves beyond the rhetoric of wartime loyalties and reveals how the legacy of war complicated colonial politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356442840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773564428423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773564428/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles